{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nThe 2026-07-08 principal-architect audit (Reliability finding #3) found reconciler safety mechanisms that are implemented, tested, and **never called in production** - the safety they promise is illusory:\n\n1. **Create->label crash window double-creates Jira issues.** `dispatch_one.py:241-256` runs `create_issue` -> adds the `rebar-id:` label the JQL dedup keys on -> binds in memory only; bindings persist only at end of pass. A hard crash between create and label leaves an orphan issue invisible to dedup; the re-run duplicates it.\n2. **The write-ahead/recovery protocol is dead code - and miswired.** `bind_pending` has zero production callers, and `run_differs.py:351` passes the applier MODULE (no `search_issues`) to `recover_pending_bindings`, so real recovery `AttributeError`s into a fail-open swallow.\n3. **Crashed pass deadlocks reconciliation forever.** Lease `steal()` is implemented/tested (`_ref_lock.py:516-535`) but the held-ref path unconditionally exits 3 (`__main__.py:499-505`); after SIGKILL the remote `refs/reconciler/lock` persists until an operator hand-deletes it.\n4. **The REST-transport write path never retries transient HTTP failures.** `acli_rest.py:61-63` re-raises every `HTTPError` and `_call_with_retry` (`dispatch_one.py:100-144`) only retries `JiraAPIError`, which the raw-`HTTPError` REST path never raises. **This benefits the REST-transport writes** (`add_label`, `set_entity_property`, transitions - the methods that route through `acli_rest` and can raise raw `HTTPError`). It does NOT change `create_issue`, which routes through the `acli_subprocess` floor and raises `CalledProcessError`/`RuntimeError` (never `HTTPError`/`JiraAPIError`); create's own 429 resilience is C4's subprocess backoff loop, and create's idempotency guarantee is the write-ahead recovery (D1), NOT this retry layer.\n\n## What\n\nWire each mechanism into its intended call site, smallest-change-first (see Design decisions D1-D4, Sequencing, Findings triage).\n\n1. **Revive the retry layer WITHOUT a boundary translation.** Extend `_call_with_retry` (dispatch_one.py:100-144) to ALSO recognize a retryable `urllib.error.HTTPError` (429; 5xx) in addition to `JiraAPIError`, leaving acli_rest's raw-`HTTPError` raise UNCHANGED. Non-retryable 4xx propagate raw. Backoff per ADR 0036: honor `Retry-After` when present; else `2**(attempt+1) + rand[0,1)` s, capped 60s; max_retries=3.\n2. **Write-safety via a per-retry dedup guard on CREATE.** Wrap `create_issue` in a dedup-aware callable that, at the START of every `_call_with_retry` attempt, INVALIDATES the search cache for the rebar-id JQL and re-runs the search, short-circuiting to the existing issue if the key now exists. (This fires only when create surfaces a `_call_with_retry`-retryable exception - `JiraAPIError`/`HTTPError`; create's subprocess-floor 429 is C4's and its crash-idempotency is D1. The guard is the belt to D1's suspenders and prevents a cache-stale double-create.) Comments are scoped OUT (D2).\n3. **Deterministic write-ahead recovery (D1).** Persist `bind_pending` BEFORE `create_issue`; on the returned key, `record_pending_key(local_id, jira_key)` and persist AGAIN BEFORE `add_label`. Hoist the `AcliClient` (built at run_differs.py:393) ABOVE the recovery call; pass it (not the applier module) to `recover_pending_bindings`. LOUD failures: `alert_store` bridge alert + a nonzero `recovery_failures` pass tally.\n4. **Crashed-pass lease steal (D3).** In `__main__.py`'s held-lock path, attempt `steal()` instead of unconditional exit 3, behind kill-switch `REBAR_RECONCILER_LOCK_STEAL` (default ON).\n\n## Scope\n\nIn:\n- `dispatch_one.py`: `_call_with_retry` HTTPError-aware (429/5xx, ADR-0036 backoff); dedup-guarded `create_issue` callable (cache-invalidate + re-search per attempt); `bind_pending`+persist before create, `record_pending_key`+persist after create/before label; **unwrap `add_comment` from `_call_with_retry` at BOTH `:341` (create) and `:610` (update)** -> single-attempt bare call feeding the existing `comment_errors` list (D2).\n- `acli.py`: add `invalidate_search_cache(jql: str) -> None` (pops `_search_cache[jql]`) so the create dedup guard never reads the stale cached pre-create empty result.\n- `run_differs.py`: hoist the `AcliClient` above the recovery call; pass it to `recover_pending_bindings` with a `failure_sink` list; emit an `alert_store` alert per failure.\n- `binding_store.py`: add `record_pending_key(local_id, jira_key) -> None` (sets `jira_key` on an existing pending entry, keeps `state='pending'`, `save()`s); add a `BindingPersistError`; extend `recover_pending_bindings(client, *, failure_sink: list[dict] | None = None) -> int` (**return type stays `int`** - existing `test_binding_store.py` int assertions unaffected) with the deterministic branch (confirm a keyed-pending record with NO Jira search; keyless -> `search_issues` fallback; append `{local_id, reason}` to `failure_sink` on error); update the module docstring to record the keyed-pending invariant.\n- `reconcile.py`: thread `recovery_failures` (= `len(failure_sink)`) into the pass `result` dict (beside `mutation_failures`) and the `sync_pass_end` log.\n- `__main__.py`: hoist `pass_id` generation ABOVE the `check_pass_lock` block (so it is the `steal()` holder); held-lock path calls `steal_pass_lock` and, on a steal-win, sets `acquired=True`, threads the new oid into `lock_oid`, starts the heartbeat, and SKIPS the unconditional `acquire_pass_lock`; `REBAR_RECONCILER_LOCK_STEAL` kill-switch.\n- `_advisory_lock.py`: thin `steal_pass_lock(holder, repo_root, *, sleep_fn=time.sleep) -> str | None` wrapping `_ref_lock.steal(...)`.\n- Tests: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/` (retry/dedup/recovery/steal) and `tests/scripts/bridge/`.\n\nRead-only (relied on, not changed): `acli_rest.py` (raw HTTPError raise UNCHANGED); `_ref_lock.py` (`steal()` already implemented).\n\nOut (justified): bulk-path 429 + `_call_with_backoff` (C4); inbound status mapping (audit-remediation epic). Deferred with rationale (Findings triage): unresolvable-pending TTL; live E2E run; `recovery_failures` as an exit gate.\n\n## Design decisions (round 4-5, resolved from code facts)\n\n- **D1 - create->label window closed DETERMINISTICALLY.** acli `create_issue` cannot carry the rebar-id label atomically (`--labels` is a destructive SET-REPLACE). Instead the pending binding records the `jira_key` the instant `create_issue` returns (persisted before `add_label`), so `recover_pending_bindings` confirms a keyed pending record with NO Jira search. Only a keyless pending record uses the label `search_issues` fallback. **bind_pending / record_pending_key persist failure is ITEM-SCOPED, not pass-scoped:** it raises `BindingPersistError`, caught by the applier's existing per-mutation error boundary so the mutation outcome gets an `error` key (which increments `mutation_failures` via the existing outcome accounting) AND an `alert_store` alert is emitted; the pass CONTINUES with the remaining mutations (a durable pending record is a precondition for a safe create, so this create is skipped rather than run without one). Setter: `record_pending_key(local_id, jira_key)`. **Post-rollback schema state:** a keyed-pending record is `{state:'pending', jira_key:'PROJ-N', created_at, updated_at}` - additive to the existing pending shape; an OLD (pre-plan) `recover_pending_bindings` ignores the extra `jira_key` field, treats it as an ordinary pending, and label-searches (still resolves, since the label was attached before confirm) - no corruption, no orphan.\n- **D2 - comments scoped OUT of the retry/dedup guard.** No cheap Jira-side idempotency key exists for a comment (posted verbatim through `acli_subprocess`), and a duplicate comment is low-harm vs. a duplicate issue; a visible `[rebar-cid]` trailer would pollute every synced comment. So `add_comment` is unwrapped from `_call_with_retry` at `dispatch_one.py:341` AND `:610` and posted SINGLE-attempt; a failed post appends to the existing non-fatal `comment_errors` list and is re-emitted by the comment differ next pass (eventually-consistent). The real failure `add_comment` raises is `AcliMutationError`/`RetryExhaustedError` (subprocess floor), NOT `HTTPError` - the test injects that real type and asserts exactly one call.\n- **D3 - lease expiry uses `steal()` itself.** `_ref_lock` treats `heartbeat_ns` as diagnostic-only and determines expiry behaviorally via `steal()` (read -> sleep one `lease_secs` -> re-check `(oid,fence)` progress). Held-lock path calls `advisory.steal_pass_lock(pass_id, repo_root)`:\n  - **new oid** -> stale lease STOLEN: set `acquired=True`, thread the new oid into `lock_oid`, START the heartbeat against it (mirroring `__main__.py:544-549`), SKIP the unconditional `acquire_pass_lock`, proceed.\n  - **None** -> re-read the ref: **still held** (live holder) -> **exit 3**; **freed** (holder released during our sleep) -> normal `acquire_pass_lock` (won -> proceed; lost to a racer -> exit 3).\n  `pass_id` is generated BEFORE the lock check so it is the steal `holder`. Steal sleeps one `lock_lease_secs` (default 120s); a structured log is emitted at the START of the sleep and on a successful steal (prior holder + new oid, `lease_steal` event); `sleep_fn` is injected in tests. The whole branch is behind `REBAR_RECONCILER_LOCK_STEAL` (default ON) - OFF reverts to unconditional exit-3 (ops back-out, tested).\n- **D4 - `recovery_failures` threading (non-breaking).** `recover_pending_bindings(client, *, failure_sink=None) -> int` KEEPS its `int` return (recovered count); failures are appended to the caller-supplied `failure_sink` list. `run_differs` owns the sink and threads its length onto the pass context/return; `reconcile.py` reads it into the `result` dict (beside `mutation_failures`) and `sync_pass_end`. Observability-only, intentionally NOT wired into `__main__.py`'s `mutation_failures` exit gate (`:345`): recovery is best-effort/fail-open, so a transient Jira search hiccup must not fail an otherwise-clean pass.\n\n## Sequencing (one change, addresses decomposition finding)\n\nThe four fixes are the single \"revive the dead reconciler safety machinery\" workstream from the audit; each has its OWN independent unit test and none depends on another's runtime, but they share one small reconciler test surface and overlap in `dispatch_one.py` (retry + write-ahead). Landing them as one Gerrit change avoids four near-trivial stacked changes with repeated rebase/review overhead; each AC is independently verifiable. Fix 4 is additionally behind its own kill-switch, disable-able in production independent of the others.\n\n## Findings triage (deferrals justified)\n\n- **Unresolvable-pending TTL/retirement** (0.264): DEFERRED to a discovered-from follow-up; a pending record that cannot resolve stays pending and re-alerts each pass (24h-deduped).\n- **Live end-to-end AC** (0.0): DEFERRED - this ticket is code-only per the epic decomposition; live exercise is owned by sibling D1 (close-ferreous-cardinal) + the reconcile-bridge GHA.\n- **`recovery_failures` exit gate** (0.0): INTENTIONAL non-gate - see D4.\n- **JQL eventual-consistency TOCTOU** (0.0): ACKNOWLEDGED residual - D1's keyed-pending write-ahead is the durable mitigation (next pass recovers via the recorded key, no search); the in-pass residual cannot be fully eliminated (Jira offers no create idempotency token). The cache-invalidate in mechanism 2 removes the STALE-CACHE duplicate, not the index-lag one.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `_call_with_retry` retries a retryable `HTTPError`: 429 honoring `Retry-After` when PRESENT, else jittered backoff (`2**(attempt+1)+rand[0,1)`, cap 60s); 5xx with the same backoff; non-retryable 4xx re-raised. WITHOUT translating at `acli_rest.py` - a test asserts the raw `HTTPError` raise from `acli_rest` is unchanged so raw-`HTTPError` catchers (e.g. apply_handlers.py:151's 404) still see raw `HTTPError`. Both header-present and header-absent 429 paths tested. Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_retry_httperror.py`.\n- [ ] The dedup-aware **create** wrapper invalidates the rebar-id JQL search cache and re-runs the search at the START of every retry attempt, short-circuiting to the existing issue if the key now exists - a test seeds the cache with an empty pre-create result, lands the create, injects a retryable `JiraAPIError` 429, and asserts the retry's cache-invalidated search finds the issue so NO duplicate is created. **Comments post single-attempt** (D2): a test injects `AcliMutationError`/`RetryExhaustedError` on `add_comment` and asserts it is called EXACTLY once (unwrapped at both `:341` and `:610`) and recorded to `comment_errors` (no duplicate). Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_create_dedup_guard.py`.\n- [ ] Write-ahead is deterministic (D1): `bind_pending` persisted BEFORE `create_issue`; `record_pending_key` persisted BEFORE `add_label`. `recover_pending_bindings` confirms any keyed-pending record (retro-attaching the label idempotently) with NO Jira search -> crash between create and label yields NO duplicate; keyless pending falls back to `search_issues` (confirm if found, else unbind). Tests: (a) crash after create+key-persist, before label -> next pass confirms, no duplicate; (b) crash before create -> fallback unbind; (c) `record_pending_key`/`bind_pending` persist failure raises `BindingPersistError`, records the mutation as failed (mutation_failures increments) + emits an `alert_store` alert, pass continues. Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_write_ahead_recovery.py`.\n- [ ] `recover_pending_bindings` receives the hoisted `AcliClient` (exposing `search_issues`, not the applier module) and a `failure_sink` list (its `int` return is unchanged); a recovery failure appends to `failure_sink`, emits an `alert_store` bridge alert, AND surfaces a nonzero `recovery_failures` (=`len(failure_sink)`) on the pass `result` + `sync_pass_end` log, instead of the silent swallow. Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_recovery_loud_failures.py`.\n- [ ] Held-lock path (D3, behind `REBAR_RECONCILER_LOCK_STEAL`) - FIVE test cases with injected `sleep_fn`: (1) steal returns new oid -> `acquired=True`, oid threaded into `lock_oid`, heartbeat started, acquire skipped, proceed; (2) None + still-held -> exit 3; (3a) None + freed + acquire wins -> proceed; (3b) None + freed + acquire lost -> exit 3; (4) kill-switch OFF -> unconditional exit 3 (no steal attempted). Proof: `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/test_lock_steal.py`.\n- [ ] Both test locations green: `python -m pytest tests/scripts/bridge/ -q` AND `python -m pytest tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/ -q`.\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783573424615060001,"uuid":"65b5cff7-b1b3-4f88-b373-54ff44486fb6"}